    <example id="exam-00003">
    <title>Determining Reasonable Values for Length</title>
    <exercise id="exer-00005">
    <problem id="prob-00005">
    <para id="para-00016">What is a reasonable value for the length of a person’s thumb: 5 meters, 5 centimeters, or 5 millimeters?</para>
    </problem>
    <solution id="sol-00003">
    <para id="para-00017">Given that a meter is slightly longer than a yard, 5 meters is not a reasonable value for the length of a person’s thumb. Since a millimeter is 10 times smaller than a centimeter, which is approximately <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mrow></math> inch, 5 millimeters is not a reasonable estimate for the length of a person’s thumb. The correct answer is 5 centimeters.</para>
    </solution>
    </exercise>
    </example>
    <note class="your-turn" id="note-00005" xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml">
    <exercise id="exer-00006">
    <problem id="prob-00006">
    <para id="para-00018"><link class="os-embed" url="#exercise/CM-C09-M1-Q003"/></para>
    </problem>
    </exercise>
    </note>
    </section>
    <section id="sect-00004">
    <title>Converting Metric Units of Measure</title>
    <para id="para-00019">Imagine you order a textbook online and the shipping detail indicates the weight of the book is 1 kg. By attaching the letter “k” to the base unit of gram (g), the unit used to express the measure is <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow></math>or 1,000 times greater than a gram. One kilogram is equivalent to 1,000 grams.</para>
    <para id="para-00020" xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml">The tip of a highlighter measures approximately 1 cm. The letter “c” attached to the base unit of meter (m) means the unit used to express the measure is <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo rspace="0.28em"/><mi>or</mi><mo rspace="0.28em"/><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mn>100</mn></mrow></mfrac></mrow></math> of a meter. One meter is equivalent to 100 centimeters.</para>
    <para id="para-00022" xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml">A <emphasis effect="bold">conversion factor</emphasis> is used to convert from smaller metric units to bigger metric units and vice versa. It is a number that when used with multiplication or division converts from one metric unit to another, both having the same base unit. In the metric system, these conversion factors are directly related to the powers of 10. The most common used conversion factors are shown in <link target-id="fig-00003" document="m00069">Figure 9.4</link>.</para>
    <figure class="numbered" id="fig-00003">
    <media alt="An illustration shows four units: kilometer, meter, centimeter, and millimeter. An illustration shows four units: mega liter, kiloliter, liter, and milliliter. An illustration shows four units: kilogram, gram, centigram, and milligram." longdesc="An arrow labeled times 1000 from kilometer points to meter. An arrow labeled times 100 from meter points to centimeter. An arrow labeled times 10 from centimeter points to millimeter. An arrow labeled divided by 10 from millimeter points to centimeter. An arrow labeled divided by 100 from centimeter points to meter. An arrow labeled divided by 1000 from meter points to kilometer. An arrow labeled times 1000 from mega liter points to kiloliter. An arrow labeled times 1000 from kiloliter points to liter. An arrow labeled times 1000 from liter points to milliliter. An arrow labeled divided by 1000 from milliliter points to liter. An arrow labeled divided by 1000 from liter points to kiloliter. An arrow labeled divided by 1000 from kiloliter points to mega liter. An arrow labeled times 1000 from kilogram points to gram. An arrow labeled times 100 from gram points to centigram. An arrow labeled times 10 from centigram points to milligram. An arrow labeled divided by 10 from milligram points to centigram. An arrow labeled divided by 100 from centigram points to gram. An arrow labeled divided by 1000 from gram points to kilogram.">
    <image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/CS_Figure_09_01_002.png"/>
