    <example id="exam-00009">
    <title>Comparing Different Units</title>
    <exercise id="exer-00017">
    <problem id="prob-00017">
    <para id="para-00048">A student carefully measured 0.52 cg of copper for a science experiment, but their lab partner said they need 6 mg of copper total. How many more centigrams of copper does the student need to add?</para>
    </problem>
    <solution id="sol-00009">
    <para id="para-00049"><emphasis effect="bold">Step 1:</emphasis> Convert these two measurements into a common unit. Since the question asks for the number of centigrams, convert 6 mg to centigrams, which is 0.6 cg.</para>
    <para id="para-00050"><emphasis effect="bold">Step 2:</emphasis> Find the difference by subtracting <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mn>0.6</mn><mo>−</mo><mn>0.52</mn></mrow></math> which is 0.08 cg. This means the student must add another 0.08 cg of copper.</para>
    </solution>
    </exercise>
    </example>
